Inferring Breast Cancer Risk with Genetic Data

Julian McClellan

8/13/2020

Overview

Using Efficient Local Ancestry Inference (ELAI) we will estimate SNP allele dosages for a sample of African Americans using source populations from West Africa and Northern/Western Europe.

Combining the ELAI results with the cancer statuses of the sample individuals, we will fit a model to infer breast cancer risk.

Data

  • 3686 individuals in the sample cohort
  • 173 individuals in the reference panel

Transformations

Both the cohort files and panel files end up as bimbam format files for entry use in ELAI.

Sample preprocessing

Reference Preprocessing

Bimbam Processing

  • For the *geno.txt files for the cohort and panel, the number of SNPs must be put on the 2nd row.

Bimbam Processing

  • For the sample position files the chromsome ID is added.

Bimbam Processing

  • For the reference *geno.txt files, we add an "=" after the number of individuals because these genotypes are phased, that is, we can identify which chromosome the genotypes alleles are from.

Ancestry Inference

ELAI uses a two-layer Hidden Markov model to infer local ancestry of admixed individuals.

Given our sample of African Americans . . .

  • African Americans have 2 source populations:
    • West Africans
    • Northern/Western Europeans
  • These 2 source populations began to mix ~10 generations ago.

These facts inform our final ELAI command.

ELAI Command

ELAI Output | Dosage

  • A file containing a table with dimensions \((S, M, N)\), where:
    • \(S\) corresponds to the number of source populations (2)
    • \(M\) to the number of SNPs present in all position and genotype files.
      chromosome SNPs
      21 20352
      22 21244
    • \(N\) to the number of admixed individuals in the sample (3686).
  • For a given \(s\), \(m\), and \(n\) in the file we will see the expected number of alleles from the \(s\)th source population for \(m\)th marker for \(n\)th individual. (allele dosage \(\in[0,2]\))

ELAI Output | SNP Info

  • A file showing information on the SNPs.
    • rsID
    • minor allele
    • major allele
    • minor allele frequency
    • major allele frequency
    • position

Cancer Risk Inference

By combining elements of the ELAI input and output, we can create a file suitable for cancer risk inference, a \(N \times M\) file where individual cancer statuses and rsIDs of SNPs can be identified.

So for a given chromsome(s) with \(M\) SNPs we model an individual \(i\)s cancer status as:



\[cancer\_status_{i} \sim allele\_dosage_{i1} + \ \cdot\cdot\cdot \ + allele\_dosage_{iM}\]

Logistic LASSO Regression

  • LASSO has the nice property of zeroing out coefficients.
    • Can allow a simpler model that focuses on the most relevant SNP predictors.
  • Model selection chooses the model with highest ROC using:
    • Scaled data (all dosages have SD of 1).
    • 90% of the data is utilized for training, with 10% reserved to assess model performance.
    • 10 fold cross validation repeated 10 times across 100 possible lambda values (equidistant on log scale from .001 to 100).


Models

  1. 20352 SNPs from Chromosome 21
  2. 21244 SNPs from Chromosome 22
  3. 41596 SNPs from Chromosomes 21 + 22 (separate ELAI runs)

Potential Adjustments: Transformation

  • Could do file format transformations without fcgene.
    • plink1.9 offers bimbam output that differs slightly from fcgene's, but should still work in ELAI.

Potential Adjustments: Ancestry Inference

  • ELAI author recommends averaging results over different mixture generation numbers.
    • Joint model fitting: Running EM steps on source and admixed samples is also recommended by the author.
  • Could increase # of EM runs above 30.
  • ELAI can be run with SNPs from multiple chromosomes simultaneously.
    • Some further adjustment of ELAI input position files would be necessary.

Potential Adjustments: Cancer Risk Inference

  • Various different models, feature selection, parameter tuning schemes, etc.
  • Utilize selected SNPs from LASSO in plain logistic regression (to get SEs for coefficients)
